x4freetext: Experiment was performed at the
flight path 14 at the Manuel Lujan, Jr., Neutron
Scattering Center at the Los Alamos Neutron Science
Center
A metallic foil of radioactive 63Ni sample was
produced by the neutron radiation of enriched 62Ni with
10.5 mm diameter and a total mass of 347 mg, in the
research reactor at the Institute Laue-Langevin (ILL)
Grenoble more than 20 years ago. This irradiation
lasted for 280 days with a thermal neutron flux of
5.5+14/s and resulted in a 63/62Ni ratio of
Gamma capture events were detected with DANCE,
a high-efficiency detector for gamma cascades
able to run in a calorimetric mode. The array
consists of 160 spherically arranged BaF2 crystals
covering a solid angle of 3.6 Pi. The inner and outer
radii of the BaF2 sphere are 17 and 32 cm. The space
between the beam pipe and the crystals is filled with
a 6LiH spherical shell, which significantly reduces
the background induced by scattered neutrons captured
in the crystals.
Energy of incident neutrons was determined by
time of flight. The facility offers a white
spallation neutron source, driven by a 100 mu-A pulsed
proton beam at a repetition rate of 20 Hz. The flight
path length was 20.29 m.
Gamma rays were identified by analysing the shape
of detector signals registered using digital data
acquisition system with 500 MHz sampling rate.
White neutron spectrum was produced by
spallation reaction of 800 MeV protons on tungsten
target
Compiled by S.H.
Data presented in fig. 10 of the reference
sent by author (M.W.)
Statistical uncertainty
Systematic uncertainty
Total uncertainty
Data were corrected for background and neutron
scattering. Background had several components, which
were corrected by measurement of empty target holder
- from natural radioactivity
- beam induced background
Correction for sample induced background caused by
major contaminant 62Ni was obtained by placing cuts at
energy corresponding to Q values of 63Ni(n,g) and
62Ni(n,g) reactions and a separate measurement with
a pure 62Ni sample.
Data were corrected for neutron scattering on 62Ni
nuclei in the sample by means of Monte Carlo simulation
based on the cross section data from JEFF 3.0/A.
